#: admin/views/template_rm_form_settings.php:51
msgid ""
"Remember - each form will have its own dashboard; accessible by clicking "
"DASHBOARD on its form card. That's how you reached here, right? But once "
"you're here, you do not need to go back to open another form's dashboard. You "
"can just..."
msgstr ""

#: admin/views/template_rm_form_settings.php:52
msgid "This of course, is your currently selected form's name. And..."
msgstr ""

#: admin/views/template_rm_form_settings.php:53
msgid "You can start adding a new form from right here."
msgstr ""

#: admin/views/template_rm_form_settings.php:54
msgid ""
"This line graph shows how your form is performing. It displays your form "
"views/ visits vs the number of times the form was filled and submitted."
msgstr ""

#: admin/views/template_rm_form_settings.php:55
msgid ""
"By default it displays stats from last 30 days. But you can change that "
"easily from this dropdown. You can find more stats in the Analytics section."
msgstr ""

#: admin/views/template_rm_form_settings.php:56
msgid "This area below contains all the sections within this form."
msgstr ""

#: admin/views/template_rm_form_settings.php:57
msgid ""
"While the <b>Design</b> takes care of the look of your form, <b>Pages and "
"Field</b> decide its content. A form is made up of fillable fields. For "
"example, Name, Email, Address etc. You can create, edit and manage fields "
"from this section."
msgstr ""

#: admin/views/template_rm_form_settings.php:58
msgid ""
"This is where you tweak individual elements of your form to make the overall "
"look match with your website's theme or experiment with different "
"combinations. "
msgstr ""

#: admin/views/template_rm_form_settings.php:60
msgid ""
"All the form specific tweaks and settings go here. Remember, these are "
"separate from Global Settings which apply to all the forms."
msgstr ""

#: admin/views/template_rm_form_settings.php:61
msgid ""
"General Settings cover the basic properties of your form, like its Name, "
"Description etc."
msgstr ""

#: admin/views/template_rm_form_settings.php:62
msgid ""
"Now this is important! This section decides properties of  WordPress User "
"accounts created when a person submits this form."
msgstr ""

#: admin/views/template_rm_form_settings.php:63
msgid ""
"Things do not end with submitting the form. You may want to show a success "
"message or a token number or perhaps redirect the user to another page with "
"relevant information. All that and more is configured through this section."
msgstr ""

#: admin/views/template_rm_form_settings.php:64
msgid ""
"Automatically send users an email notification with customized content after "
"they have submitted the form."
msgstr ""

#: admin/views/template_rm_form_settings.php:65
msgid ""
"Limits allow you to set, well, limits to your form. Once a limit is reached, "
"the form goes to <i>expired</i> state. This will also be visible on the form "
"card. Limits are useful if you have limited submission slots or if "
"registration is only open before a specified date."
msgstr ""

#: admin/views/template_rm_form_settings.php:66
msgid ""
"Access Control allows you to lock the form and visitor will only be allowed "
"to see it if they meets certain parameters. For example, if you want to allow "
"registrations for people only above 18 years, you can set Date of Birth as "
"access control."
msgstr ""

#: admin/views/template_rm_form_settings.php:67
msgid ""
"You can tweak content of the emails being sent out to the users filling this "
"form from here."
msgstr ""

#: admin/views/template_rm_form_settings.php:68
msgid ""
"<b>Overrides</b> are basically Global Settings which can be over ridden "
"specific to a form. This is useful when you have lots of forms and you want "
"one or some of the forms to have separate configuration compared to others. "
"Remember, not all settings can be over ridden. Only those which can, will "
"appear here."
msgstr ""

#: admin/views/template_rm_form_settings.php:70
msgid ""
"All form specific integrations can be found in this section. System specific "
"integrations are in Global Settings --> External Integration"
msgstr ""

#: admin/views/template_rm_form_settings.php:71
msgid ""
"If you are using <b>MailChimp</b>, you can use options here to send your form "
"data to a MailChimp user list. Make sure you configure your MailChimp account "
"in RegistrationMagic -> Global Settings -> External Integrations first. "
msgstr ""

#: admin/views/template_rm_form_settings.php:72
msgid ""
"Add extra bells and whistles to your site by attaching your user registration "
"system to ProfileGrid’s advance user profiles and groups system."
msgstr ""

#: admin/views/template_rm_form_settings.php:74
msgid ""
"Publish forms and user details on frontend using different methods described "
"below."
msgstr ""

#: admin/views/template_rm_form_settings.php:75
msgid "Learn how to use shortcode to publish this form on a page or post."
msgstr ""

#: admin/views/template_rm_form_settings.php:76
msgid "Learn how to use WordPress theme widgets to publish this form."
msgstr ""

#: admin/views/template_rm_form_settings.php:77
msgid ""
"Learn how to publish a user account area for registered users on the "
"frontend. "
msgstr ""

#: admin/views/template_rm_form_settings.php:78
msgid ""
"Configure a clickable button with popup on the frontend which allows users to "
"quickly fill forms, login and check their details."
msgstr ""

#: admin/views/template_rm_form_settings.php:79
msgid "Learn how to publish this form inside a landing page on the frontend. "
msgstr ""

#: admin/views/template_rm_form_settings.php:80
msgid "Learn how to publish login form for your users. "
msgstr ""

#: admin/views/template_rm_form_settings.php:81
msgid ""
"Learn how to allow non-registered users to check their form submissions.  "
msgstr ""

#: admin/views/template_rm_form_settings.php:83
msgid ""
"Manage data collection and user interactions through this form from this "
"section."
msgstr ""

#: admin/views/template_rm_form_settings.php:84
#, php-format
msgid ""
"Like this very important form <b>Inbox</b>. This is where all user submission "
"records for <b>%s</b> go."
msgstr ""

#: admin/views/template_rm_form_settings.php:85
#, php-format
msgid ""
"See this badge? This tell you the number of time users have filled and "
"submitted this form. Right now there are <b>%d</b> submissions associated "
"with your form <b>%s</b>"
msgstr ""

#: admin/views/template_rm_form_settings.php:86
msgid ""
"If your form has a file upload field(s), all the attachments go here. "
"Remember, attachments are also visible inside individual submission records "
"in <b>Inbox</b>. But think of this as a bucket where files are stored "
"individually. If you want to download all of them as a zip, this is the place."
msgstr ""

#: admin/views/template_rm_form_settings.php:87
msgid "All the outgoing emails to the users are recorded in this area."
msgstr ""

#: admin/views/template_rm_form_settings.php:89
msgid ""
"<b>Analytics</b>, as the name suggests, collects and displays all the stats "
"related to this form as table, graphs and charts."
msgstr ""

#: admin/views/template_rm_form_settings.php:90
msgid ""
"<b>Field Analytics</b>, collects and displays stats related to individual "
"fields inside the form. It can only display meaningful stats from pre-set "
"option field types like <i>dropdown, checkbox or radiobox</i>"
msgstr ""

#: admin/views/template_rm_form_settings.php:92
msgid ""
"This is a powerful system which allows you to 'program' the form to do "
"essential workflow tasks for you. We recommend visiting it after you have "
"familiarized yourself with other areas of the form."
msgstr ""

#: admin/views/template_rm_form_settings.php:93
msgid ""
"This section allows you to email all the users who have submitted this form. "
"You'll find this useful for broadcasting announcements and sending bulk "
"updates."
msgstr ""

#: admin/views/template_rm_form_settings.php:95
msgid ""
"We hope you liked what you have seen so far! Let's move on to the two "
"Sidebars."
msgstr ""

#: admin/views/template_rm_form_settings.php:97
msgid ""
"Click here, and a drop down will appear with list of your forms. And you just "
"have to choose another form from the list. You can try that later. Let's move "
"on..."
msgstr ""

#: admin/views/template_rm_form_settings.php:98
msgid ""
"This is form's unique embed code. As the name suggests, you can use this code "
"to embed the form where WordPress shortcode would not work. Like an external "
"webpage. Otherwise, shortcode is always the best way to display the form."
msgstr ""

#: admin/views/template_rm_form_settings.php:99
msgid "First one is sort of live update feed for your form."
msgstr ""

#: admin/views/template_rm_form_settings.php:100
msgid ""
"And the next one is very similar to what you find inside WordPress pages and "
"posts. It provides surface view of the form."
msgstr ""

#: admin/views/template_rm_form_settings.php:101
msgid ""
"The first block on this sidebar shows submissions feed as users submit the "
"forms. Initially, when there are no submissions, it will simply show \"0\". "
"It'll look a lot different when the submissions start."
msgstr ""

#: admin/views/template_rm_form_settings.php:102
msgid "You can view all submissions by clicking on this button."
msgstr ""

#: admin/views/template_rm_form_settings.php:103
msgid ""
"The second block shows a list of files received through your form. If you do "
"not have a file upload field inside your form, this area will stay empty and "
"you can ignore it."
msgstr ""

#: admin/views/template_rm_form_settings.php:104
msgid "You can view all attachments anytime by clicking on this button."
msgstr ""

#: admin/views/template_rm_form_settings.php:105
msgid ""
"This is the shortcode for this form. As you already know, you need to paste "
"the shortcode where you wish to show the form. You can simply copy the "
"shortcode..."
msgstr ""

#: admin/views/template_rm_form_settings.php:106
msgid "By clicking"
msgstr ""

#: admin/views/template_rm_form_settings.php:107
msgid ""
"Visiblity of the form defines if the form is visible to all users who have "
"access to form page or if the access control is on. We have already discussed "
"how to open Access Control section. Clicking <i>Edit</i> will take you "
"directly to it."
msgstr ""

#: admin/views/template_rm_form_settings.php:108
msgid ""
"If you wish to delete this form (with all its contents, stats and "
"submissions), you can do that by clicking Delete. To delete multiple forms, "
"use batch selection checkboxes in Forms Manager."
msgstr ""

#: admin/views/template_rm_form_settings.php:109
msgid ""
"Your form can be spread over multiple pages. This number shows the count of "
"pages in your form."
msgstr ""

#: admin/views/template_rm_form_settings.php:110
msgid ""
"This shows the number of fields on your form across all pages. For example, a "
"form can have 3 pages with 5 fields on each page. The total field count will "
"be 15."
msgstr ""

#: admin/views/template_rm_form_settings.php:111
msgid ""
"While fields are managed by <b>Pages and Fields</b> section, you can also "
"quickly add a new field by clicking <i>Add</i> here."
msgstr ""

#: admin/views/template_rm_form_settings.php:112
msgid ""
"This is the label of the submit button of your form. It can be labelled "
"Submit, Register, Send or anything you please. To change it, you can click on "
"<i>Change</i> button on the right side. You can fully customise the look of "
"the Submit button by visiting <b>Design</b> section."
msgstr ""

#: admin/views/template_rm_form_settings.php:113
msgid ""
"You can create a clone of this form by clicking <i>Duplicate</i>. It will "
"have same content, design and field/ pages."
msgstr ""

#: admin/views/template_rm_form_settings.php:114
msgid ""
"This number shows the total number of visitors (or views) of your form during "
"last 30 days."
